Catalase is required for peroxisome maintenance during adipogenesis

Highlights

  • •
    It is necessary to clarify the underlying mechanism of lipid accumulation.
  • •
    Increased catalase activity and lipid accumulation were observed during the differentiation of preadipocytes 3T3-L1.
  • •
    Inhibition of catalase activity resulted in reduced lipid accumulation, increased H2O2 levels and occurrence of autophagy.
  • •
    Catalase protects against the degradation of peroxisomes via autophagy triggered by the generation of H2O2 in peroxisomes.

Abstract

Although obesity contributes to the onset and pathogenesis of metabolic diseases, it has been repeatedly demonstrated that being overweight or mildly obese carries a survival advantage compared with being thin or normal-weight. This relationship is called the obesity paradox. Hence, it is necessary to clarify the underlying mechanism of obesity onset for the prevention and treatment of these diseases. Catalase is distributed in peroxisomes under normal redox conditions and catalase activity is increased during the differentiation of 3T3-L1 preadipocytes to adipocytes. Although peroxisomes are responsible for lipid metabolism, the role of peroxisomal catalase in the process of lipid accumulation remains unclear. The present study aimed to investigate the relationships among catalase activity, peroxisome content, and lipid accumulation during the differentiation of 3T3-L1 preadipocytes to adipocytes. Increased catalase activity and lipid accumulation were observed during the differentiation of preadipocytes. Silencing of catalase by small interfering RNA or treatment with 3-amino-1,2,4-triazole (3-AT), a catalase inhibitor, resulted in reduced lipid accumulation. Inhibition of catalase activity in peroxisomes increases hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) levels, which results in a reduction of peroxisome content. Extracellular H2O2 had no influence on lipid accumulation during differentiation. The occurrence of autophagy was clearly enhanced in cells treated with 3-AT. Spautin-1, an inhibitor of autophagy flux, protected against a reduction in lipid accumulation by treatment with 3-AT. Our data provide evidence that catalase protects against the degradation of peroxisomes via the occurrence of autophagy triggered by the generation of H2O2 in peroxisomes. These results suggest that catalase in peroxisomes is crucial to adipogenesis.

1. Introduction

In recent decades, there has been a worldwide increase in the incidence of lipid metabolic diseases and it is important to understand the effects of obesity on critical illnesses. Although obesity contributes to the onset and pathogenesis of metabolic diseases, such as diabetes mellitus and cardiovascular disease [[1], [2], [3], [4]], it has been repeatedly demonstrated that being overweight or mildly obese carries a moderate survival advantage compared with being thinner or normal- weight [[5], [6], [7], [8]]. This relationship is called the obesity paradox, in which obesity can improve or worsen symptoms. Hence, it is necessary to clarify the underlying mechanism of obesity onset for the prevention and treatment of these diseases. Nutrient overload triggers the differentiation of preadipocytes into mature adipocytes and induces an increase in the size of lipid droplets in mature adipocytes, in a process known as adipogenesis [9,10]. Adipocytes store lipids in the form of triglycerides in lipid droplets, which are considered a marker of differentiated adipocytes. In adipose tissue, mitochondria play a key role in energy metabolism [11]. To produce the high-energy compound adenosine triphosphate, the electron transport chain pathway generates reactive oxygen species (ROS), since a proportion of the O2 molecules taken up by mitochondria are converted to superoxide anion radicals (O2−) by excessive electrons. O2− is automatically or enzymatically decomposed to H2O2 and O2. It has been demonstrated that ROS, including H2O2, also stimulate the differentiation of preadipocytes [12,13]. Thus, these findings highlight the need to consider the role of ROS in adipogenesis and the onset of obesity.
Oxidative stress under certain conditions controls cell destinies, such as proliferation, survival, and differentiation [[12], [13], [14]]. ROS derived from nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH) oxidase [13] and mitochondria [14] appear to play a role in adipogenic differentiation. ROS production by adipocytes accompanying adipogenesis was reportedly abolished by treatment with an NADPH oxidase inhibitor [15]. Moreover, ROS derived from mitochondrial complex III may promote adipogenesis via the up-regulation of the adipogenic effector CCAAT/enhancer-binding protein beta in human bone marrow-derived mesenchymal stem cells [16]. In contrast, mitochondrial ROS generated by the deletion of p66(Shc), a redox enzyme, also reduced triglyceride accumulation in adipocytes and decreased fat mass in a mouse model of diet-induced obesity [17]. These findings suggest that intracellular ROS play a role in the process of lipid accumulation in adipocytes.
The peroxisome is an organelle that plays an indispensable role in numerous metabolic pathways, including β-oxidation of very long chain fatty acids, the production and detoxification of H2O2, and the synthesis of ether phospholipids and bile acids [18]. The number of peroxisomes in the cell is maintained by a balance between biogenesis and breakdown [[19], [20], [21]]. The genes encoding for 32 peroxins are required for peroxisome biogenesis [22,23]. Impairment of peroxisome biogenesis causes metabolic disorder, termed the Zellweger spectrum, which includes Zellweger syndrome, neonatal adrenoleukodystrophy, infantile Refsum disease, and rhizomelic chondrodysplasia punctata [24]. Since the plasma content of very long chain fatty acids is increased in patients with Zellweger syndrome, Brown et al. proposed that the peroxisome is an essential organelle for lipid metabolism [25]. These findings imply that the maintenance of peroxisome number and function is important for lipid homeostasis.
Cells undergoing adipogenesis are likely to upregulate the production of antioxidant enzymes to avoid cellular damage or cell death caused by oxidative stress [[26], [27], [28]]. Catalase is an antioxidant enzyme containing heme that is distributed in the peroxisome under normal redox conditions and protects against damage by H2O2 produced by peroxisomal oxidase [29,30]. We previously demonstrated phase variations in anti-oxidative capacity during the differentiation of 3T3-L1 preadipocytes to adipocytes, indicating an increase in intracellular catalase activity and glutathione (GSH) content [26]. Although cytotoxic, H2O2 participates in adipogenesis by controlling intracellular signaling pathways [[31], [32], [33]]. Although catalase protects against oxidative stress, the role of this enzyme in lipid accumulation is unclear. Given the importance of H2O2 levels in various physiological processes, catalase might modulate lipid accumulation via regulation of peroxisomal H2O2 levels.
To maintain nutrient and energy homeostasis, autophagy is an important protective mechanism that allows cells to eliminate components damaged by oxidative stress [34,35]. Autophagy is necessary in normal adipocyte differentiation [[36], [37], [38]]. Notably, knockdown of autophagy related 5 (ATG5) or Atg7, which are autophagy related-proteins, and pharmacological inhibitors of autophagy, such as 3-methyladenine and chloroquine, resulted in the inhibition of differentiation of 3T3-L1 preadipocytes to mature adipocytes [37,39]. These findings suggest that autophagy protects against H2O2-induced oxidative stress during differentiation. However, Shen et al. proposed that autophagy may be involved in the initiation of the stress response in the induction of cell death [40]. Since severe autophagy may lead to a pro-death response, it is classified as a type II form of programed cell death [41,42]. Hence, autophagy is also associated with both cell survival and death [43]. Autophagy is observed most intensively during the initial stage of differentiation of 3T3-L1 cells [39]. However, the mechanism underlying the regulatory role of autophagy in lipid accumulation remains unclear.
The obesity-related mechanisms linking these processes in lipid accumulation must be clarified, particularly the mechanism underlying the regulatory role of catalase in adipocyte differentiation. Therefore, the aim of the present study was to elucidate the regulatory roles of catalase in intracellular lipid accumulation and the maintenance of peroxisomes during the differentiation of adipocytes. The results of this study clarify the relationship between peroxisome content, catalase activity, oxidative stress, and the occurrence of autophagy during the differentiation of preadipocytes in adipogenesis.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Materials

The following chemicals and antibodies (Abs) were used in this study: anti-LC3 monoclonal Ab (Medical & Biological Laboratories Co., Ltd., Nagoya, Japan), small interfering (si) RNA and Abs against catalase (Santa Cruz Biotechnology, Inc., Dallas, TX, USA), siRNA against peroxisomal biogenesis factor 26 (Pex26) and AccuTarget™ negative control siRNA (Bioneer Corporation, Daejeon, Korea), 3-isobutyl-1-methylxanthine, insulin solution, dexamethasone, Peroxy Orange 1 (PO1), spautin-1, bovine serum albumin radioimmunoassay-grade fraction V (Sigma-Aldrich Corporation, St. Louis, MO, USA), fetal bovine serum (FBS; MP Biomedicals, LLC, Santa Ana, CA, USA), CellLight™ Peroxisome-green fluorescent protein (GFP), BacMam 2.0 (peroxisome-GFP), Alexa Fluor™ 647 goat anti-mouse immunoglobulin (Ig)G (H + L), 0.25% trypsin-ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (1×), penicillin/streptomycin (P/S), polyclonal Ab against adenosine triphosphate-binding cassette sub-family D member 3 (PMP70; Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA), phosphate-buffered saline (PBS; Takara Bio Inc., Siga, Japan), Hoechst 33258 and Hoechst 33342 solution (Dojindo Laboratories, Kumamoto, Japan), 3-amino-1,2,4-triazole (3-AT), Dulbecco's modified Eagle's medium (high glucose) with l-glutamine and Phenol Red (DMEM), radioimmunoprecipitation assay (RIPA) buffer, ScreenFect™ siRNA, digitonin, a bicinchoninic acid (BCA) protein assay kit, 10% neutral buffered formalin solution, 4% paraformaldehyde PBS (Wako Pure Chemical Industries, Ltd., Osaka, Japan), a lipid assay kit (Cosmo Bio Co., Ltd., Tokyo, Japan), an OxiSelect™ Hydrogen Peroxide/Peroxidase Assay Kit (Cell Biolabs, Inc., San Diego, CA, USA), cOmplete™ Tablets, Mini EASYpack (Roche Diagnostics KK, Tokyo, Japan), β-actin mouse mAb (Proteintech Group, Inc., Rosemont, IL, USA), horseradish peroxidase (HRP)-conjugated goat anti-rabbit IgG (H&L) Ab (Rockland Immunochemicals, Inc., Pottstown, PA, USA), anti-mouse IgG, HRP-Linked Whole Ab Sheep and ECL Western Blotting Detection Reagents (GE Healthcare UK Ltd., Buckinghamshire, England), and EzBlock Chemi blocking reagent (Atto Corporation, Tokyo, Japan). All other chemicals were of the highest grade available from commercial supplies.

2.2. Cell culture and differentiation into adipocytes

3T3-L1 cells (American Type Culture Collection, Manassas, VA, USA) were cultured in DMEM supplemented with 1% P/S, and 10% FBS at 37 °C under a humidified atmosphere of 5% CO2/95% air. To induce differentiation, confluent preadipocytes (day 0) were cultured in DMEM containing 10% FBS, 1% P/S, 5 μg/mL of insulin, 0.1 mM 3-isobutyl-1-methylxanthine, and 1 μM dexamethasone for 3 days and then in fresh medium containing 5 μg/mL of insulin for an additional 3 days. To estimate the number of cells, cultured cells were washed with PBS and fixed with 4% paraformaldehyde PBS for 15 min at room temperature. After washing again with PBS, the fixed cells were permeabilized with methanol for 10 min at −20 °C, washed with PBS, and then stained with 1 μg/mL of Hoechst 33258 in PBS. After washing, the cells were quantified by counting the number of nuclei per unit area using the Cytell™ Cell Imaging System (GE Healthcare UK Ltd., Little Chalfont, Buckinghamshire, England).

2.3. siRNA transfection

Two days after seeding, the cells were further cultured in fresh medium and transfected with predesigned ScreenFect™ siRNA against catalase or Pex26 at a final concentration of 100 nM. The siRNA-liposome complex was prepared according to the manufacturer's protocol. The same process was performed on day 3 post differentiation. On day 2 post transfection the cells were cultured in differentiation medium. The same process was performed on day 3 post differentiation.

2.4. Lipid assay

Lipid droplets in adipocytes were stained with Oil Red O using a commercial lipid assay kit, in accordance with the manufacturer's protocol. Briefly, cells cultured in the wells of a 24-well plate were washed with PBS and fixed overnight with 10% formalin neutral buffer solution. After washing with deionized distilled water, the cells were stained with Oil Red O working solution (6:4 = 0.6% Oil Red O dye in isopropanol: deionized distilled water) for 30 min at room temperature and then washed at least three times with deionized distilled water. Afterward, the cells were observed using a bright-field microscopy. For quantification of lipid accumulation, Oil Red O was extracted using 60% isopropanol solution and quantified at a wavelength of 540 nm.

2.5. Glucose uptake assay

Glucose uptake activity was determined on the basis of 2-deoxyglucose (2DG) uptake using a 2-deoxyglucose uptake measurement kit (COSMO BIO Co. Ltd., Tokyo, Japan) in accordance with the manufacturer's protocol. Briefly, cells cultured in a 6-well plate were incubated with a serum-free DMEM at 37 °C for 6 h and then washed three times with Krebs Ringer Phosphate Hepes buffer (pH 7.5). Cells were stimulated with 5 μg/mL insulin for 18 min before incubation with 1 mM 2DG for another 20 min. After the reaction was terminated by washing in cold PBS, cells were scraped into 10 mM Tris-HCl buffer (pH 8.0) and then homogenized using an Ultrasonic disrupter (UR-21P, TOMY SEIKO Co. Ltd., Tokyo) at 28 kHz and 4 W for 15 s three times on ice. The cell lysate was centrifuged at 15,000 ×g at 4 °C for 20 min and then the supernatant was collected to measure of glucose uptake activity. A portion of the resulting supernatant was diluted 10 fold with sample diluent buffer and analyzed for 2-deoxyglucose 6-phosphate (2DG6P) content. The 2DG6P concentration was calculated using a calibration curve created with standard 2DG6P. Total cellular protein, as measured using the BCA protein assay, was used to normalize the 2DG6P concentration.

2.6. Catalase activity assay

Catalase activity was measured by monitoring the decrease in absorbance of H2O2. The cultured cells in the wells of a 24-wells plate were washed with PBS, scraped into RIPA buffer with a protease inhibitor cocktail on ice, and then homogenized using a Bioruptor® Plus sonication device (Cosmo Bio Co., Ltd.) at 20 KHz and 300 W for 30 s three times on ice. The cell lysate was centrifuged at 12,000 ×g at 4 °C for 30 min and then the supernatant was collected for measurement of catalase activity. The change in absorbance of H2O2 in Tris-HCl-ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid buffer (pH 8.0) per minute was measured at 240 nm. The extinction coefficient of 43.6 M−1 cm−1 was used to calculate catalase activity. Total cellular protein, as measured with the BCA protein assay, was used to normalize catalase activity.

2.7. Intracellular H2O2 detection

Intracellular H2O2 levels were measured using the OxiSelect™ Hydrogen Peroxide/Peroxidase Assay Kit. Briefly, the samples were incubated with 100 μM 10-acetyl-3,7-dihydroxyphenoxazine and 0.2 U/mL horseradish peroxidase in assay buffer for 30 min at room temperature, while protected from light. In the presence of horseradish peroxidase, 10-acetyl-3,7-dihydroxyphenoxazine reacts with peroxidase and produces highly fluorescent resorufin. The amount of resorufin was determined using a GloMax® Discover Microplate Reader (Promega Corporation, Milwaukee, WI, USA). The concentrations of H2O2 in the samples were determined by comparing the resorufin concentrations of the samples with a standard curve. Total cellular protein, as measured by using the BCA protein assay, was used for normalization of H2O2 levels.
H2O2 in peroxisomes was detected by fluorescence staining using PO1 and peroxisome- GFP. Peroxisome-GFP was added to cultured cells at 24 h before measurement. The cells were washed with PBS and incubated with PO1 in culture medium for 30 min at 37 °C under a humidified atmosphere of 5% CO2/95% air. After washing with PBS, images were acquired using a LSM 700 laser-scanning confocal microscope (Carl Zeiss AG, Oberkochen, Germany). H2O2 levels in peroxisomes were quantified by analyzing the fluorescence intensity of H2O2 overlapped on labeled peroxisomes using ZEISS Efficient Navigation imaging software (Carl Zeiss AG).

2.8. Immunofluorescence staining

Cells grown on glass bottom dishes were washed with ice-cold PBS and fixed with 4% paraformaldehyde PBS for 15 min. After permeabilization with 100 μg/mL of digitonin in PBS for 20 min, the cells were blocked with 3% bovine serum albumin (BSA) in PBS for 1 h and then incubated with anti-LC3 mAb (dilution, 1:500) in 1% BSA for 1 h followed by Alexa Fluor™ 647 goat anti-mouse IgG (H + L) (1:500) and 1 μg/mL of Hoechst 33258 in 1% BSA for 30 min, while protected from light. After washing, images were acquired using a LSM 700 laser-scanning confocal microscope.

2.9. Western blot analysis

The cultured cells were rinsed with PBS and scraped into RIPA buffer with complete™ Mini protease inhibitor cocktail. After measuring the protein concentration using a BCA Protein Assay Kit, cell lysate was added to the protein sample buffer and boiled at 100 °C for 20 min. Proteins (30 μg) were then separated by sodium dodecyl sulfate-polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis and transferred to a polyvinylidene difluoride membrane, which was blocked with EzBlock Chemi for 1 h at room temperature, and then incubated with a primary Ab against catalase (1:700), PMP70 (1:5000), microtubule-associated proteins 1A/1B light chain 3B (MAP1LC3, LC3, 1:5000), or β-actin (1:5000) at 4 °C overnight. Subsequently, the membranes were incubated with HRP-conjugated goat anti-rabbit IgG Ab (1:5000) or anti-mouse IgG, HRP-linked whole Ab sheep (1:5000) and horseradish peroxidase-conjugated secondary antibodies for 2 h at room temperature. The protein bands were visualized using ECL Western Blotting Detection Reagents with Ez-Capture MG (Atto Corporation). Band intensity was measured using a carbon/sulfur analyzer (Atto Corporation). In all cases, target protein expression was normalized to β-actin protein levels.

2.10. Statistical analysis

Data are presented as the mean ± standard deviation of at least three independent experiments. The Student's t-test was used to identify differences between two groups. ANOVA followed by Dunnett's test was used to determined differences among three groups. A probability (p) value of <0.05 was considered statistically significant.

3. Results

3.1. Inhibition of catalase activity reduced lipid accumulation

In order to determine the role of catalase in lipid accumulation, the impact of catalase activity on lipid accumulation during the differentiation of 3T3-L1 preadipocytes to adipocytes was assessed. As shown in Fig. 1A and B, the number and size of lipid droplets were decreased. Lipid accumulation was reduced by 36% in adipocytes treated with siRNA targeting catalase at day 6 with that in control cells, whereas negative control siRNA had no effect on lipid accumulation. The siRNA treatment reduced catalase protein expression by was 47%, whereas negative control siRNA had no effect on catalase expression (Fig. 1C). Similarly, treatment with 3-AT, an inhibitor of catalase, suppressed the formation of lipid droplets (Fig. 1D) and decreased lipid accumulation in a dose-dependent manner (45% at 10 mM; Fig. 1E), but glucose uptake capacity was not affected (Fig. 1F). Catalase activity markedly decreased in 3-AT-treated cells in a dose-dependent manner (45% at 10 mM vs. control cells; Fig. 1G). However, the addition of 3-AT resulted in no change in the number of adipocytes (Fig. 1H). These data suggest that catalase activity is necessary for lipid accumulation in 3T3-L1 adipocytes.

3.2. Generation of H2O2 in peroxisomes

To clarify whether H2O2 generation results in reduced lipid accumulation, the levels of intracellular H2O2 during preadipocyte differentiation to adipocytes were determined. As shown in Fig. 2A, intracellular H2O2 levels were significantly increased by 1.1-fold on day 3 and 1.4-fold on day 6. Treatment with 3-AT also increased intracellular H2O2 levels by 1.7-fold at 1 mM, 3.8-fold at 5 mM, and 5.5-fold at 10 mM, as compared to control cells on day 6 (Fig. 2B). In Fig. 2C, peroxisomes are indicated by green fluorescence (left panel) and the generated H2O2 is indicated by yellow fluorescence (middle panel). At 6 days after the initiation of cell differentiation with 3-AT, the generated H2O2 was localized to the cytoplasm, but not distributed throughout. Peroxisomes and the generated H2O2 were colocalized in merged images (right panel) as indicated by white allow heads (Fig. 2C). Fluorescence showing H2O2 colocalized with peroxisomes was increased by treatment with 3-AT in time-dependent manner (Fig. 2D) and fluorescence intensity was increased by about 2.2-fold as compared to the control cells at 3 and 6 days after initiation of differentiation (Fig. 2E). These results suggest that H2O2 is generated in peroxisomes during the differentiation of preadipocytes and catalase effectively blocked the increase in H2O2 levels.
In order to clarify the inhibitory effect of H2O2 on lipid accumulation, extracellular H2O2 was added to the adipocyte culture. As shown in Fig. 3A, there was no change in the number and size of lipid drops by the addition of H2O2 to cells. The addition of H2O2 at ≤100 μM had no influence on lipid accumulation (Fig. 3B) or cell number (Fig. 3C) during the differentiation of preadipocytes. However, extracellular H2O2 at ≥300 μM induced a reduction in lipid accumulation (Fig. 3B) and cell death (Fig. 3C). Based on these data, intracellular H2O2 generated in peroxisomes had an impact on lipid accumulation during the differentiation of preadipocytes.

3.3. Role of catalase and peroxisomes in lipid accumulation

To clarify the participation of peroxisomes in lipid accumulation, we investigated the reduction in the number of peroxisomes and catalase content in adipocytes. The expression levels of PMP70, a marker of peroxisomes, decreased by 40% in adipocytes following treatment with 3-AT, as compared to control cells. In the presence of rosiglitazone, the content of the peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPAR-γ) agonist PMP70 increased by 29%, as compared to control cells, and 34%, as compared to treatment with 3-AT alone (Fig. 4A). Catalase content also decreased by 57% in adipocytes treated with 3-AT alone. In the presence of rosiglitazone, catalase content significantly increased by 29%, as compared to control cells, and 25%, as compared to treatment with 3-AT alone (Fig. 4B). Treatment with 3-AT alone suppressed the accumulation of lipid droplets by 56% and coexistence with rosiglitazone recovered the suppression of lipid accumulation by 48%, as compared to treatment with 3-AT alone (Fig. 4C). Silencing of PEX26, which is involved in peroxisome synthesis, by treatment with targeted siRNA reduced the number of peroxisomes by 52%, whereas negative-control siRNA had no effect on the number of peroxisomes (Fig. 4D). As shown in Fig. 4E, the number and size of lipid droplets were decreased in adipocytes treated with PEX26 siRNA at day 6, as compared to control cells. Treatment with siRNA targeting PEX26 suppressed lipid accumulation by 26% during the differentiation of preadipocytes, whereas negative-control siRNA had no effect on lipid accumulation (Fig. 4F). These results indicate the participation of peroxisomes and catalase in lipid accumulation in 3T3-L1 adipocytes.

3.4. Effect of autophagy on lipid accumulation

Since autophagy is necessary for cellular differentiation [[38], [39], [40]], the effect of autophagy on lipid accumulation was investigated. As shown in Fig. 5A, the number of autophagosomes, as detected by green fluorescence of LC3B, an isoform of autophagy-related protein LC3, strongly increased in a time-dependent manner during the differentiation of preadipocytes. As shown in Fig. 5B and C, we observed a clear increase in the fluorescence intensity of the dye for the expression of Atg5 and LC3 proteins, which are related to the autophagy vacuoles, during the differentiation. As shown in Fig. 5D and E, treatment with 3-AT increased the intensity of green fluorescence by the formation of autophagosomes for the expression of LC3 proteins and significantly increased the LC3II/I ratio, which is an indicator of autophagy activation [34,39], by 1.4 fold. In the presence of spautin-1, a potent and specific autophagy inhibitor, lipid accumulation increased by 30%, as compared to control cells. The decrease in lipid accumulation by 3-AT treatment was recovered to 99% in the presence of spautin-1 (Fig. 5F). These results suggest that the occurrence of autophagy by 3-AT treatment resulted in the inhibition of lipid accumulation and a decrease in peroxisome content.

4. Discussion

The present study demonstrated for the first time that the catalase plays an important role in lipid accumulation during the differentiation of preadipocytes to adipocytes. Lipid droplets, which take up cytoplasmic triglycerides and cholesterol esters, markedly enlarge and increase in number during the differentiation of preadipocytes. Inhibition of the activity of catalase in 3T3-L1 cells increased intracellular H2O2 concentrations and reduced lipid accumulation, suggesting that an increase in H2O2 levels could inhibit adipogenesis. Our previous study demonstrated that catalase activity and the GSH/oxidized GSH (GSSG) ratio were increased during the differentiation of preadipocytes, thereby increasing the antioxidant capacity of mature adipocytes [28]. Catalase maintains the redox balance in peroxisomes by decomposing H2O2 into H2O and O2. GSH peroxidase also metabolizes H2O2 to H2O while oxidizing GSH to GSSG. Since GSH peroxidase has a low Km value against H2O2 than catalase, GSH may be able to participate in the metabolism of low concentrations of H2O2. Pretreatment with the GSH synthesis inhibitor buthionine-SR-sulfoximine had no effect on lipid accumulation during the differentiation of preadipocytes (data not shown). Treatment with 3-AT, an irreversible catalase inhibitor that binds to catalase-H2O2 compound I, had no direct effect on catalase synthesis or degradation, induced an increase in intracellular H2O2 levels, and decreased lipid accumulation, suggesting that intracellular H2O2 levels are controlled by catalase during the differentiation of preadipocytes. These results suggest that catalase facilitates adipogenesis by removal of excessive H2O2 during differentiation.
The results of the present study showed that catalase levels in peroxisomes are inversely correlated with intracellular levels of H2O2 in adipocytes. Since catalase is distributed in the peroxisome under normal redox conditions, it is used as a marker of peroxisomes [29,[44], [45], [46]]. Although endogenous ROS is produced mostly by cellular respiration with the production of adenosine triphosphate in mitochondria, the peroxisome is also a possible source of ROS [30]. It is estimated that about 35% of the total H2O2 in the rat liver is derived from peroxisomal oxidases, including acyl-CoA oxidase, urate oxidase, and xanthine oxidase [47]. Peroxisomes and mitochondria coordinate lipid metabolism and ROS production to establish a redox tone to control lipid metabolism [48]. In the presence of a catalase inhibitor, the number of peroxisome had decreased, while peroxisomal H2O2 levels had increased. However, we were unable to detect a decrease in mitochondria content or mitochondrial membrane potential, or an increase in ROS generation by the mitochondria of adipocytes treated with 3-AT, as compared to control cells (data not shown). We confirmed that extracellular H2O2 did not impair lipid accumulation during the differentiation of preadipocytes. These results indicate that peroxisomal H2O2 participated in the inhibition of lipid accumulation in adipocytes.
We observed both a decrease in peroxisome content and lipid accumulation in 3T3-L1 cells treated with catalase siRNA or 3-AT. Because peroxisomes are responsible for lipid metabolism, such as α-oxidation of branched chain fatty acids, β-oxidation of very long chain fatty acids, and the synthesis of ether lipids and bile acids [19,[49], [50], [51]], peroxisomes are thought to be involved in lipid accumulation as evidenced by the formation and enlargement of lipid droplets in adipocytes. We also demonstrated that treatment with rosiglitazone recovered the decrease in lipid accumulation and peroxisome contents in cells treated with 3-AT. Rosiglitazone activates peroxisome proliferation and enhances the expression of PPAR-γ and CCAAT-enhancer-binding protein α, a dominant regulator of adipogenesis- and lipid metabolism-related gene expression [[52], [53], [54]]. These finding suggest that rosiglitazone induces an increase in peroxisome content or directly enhances adipogenesis-related gene expression. Also, knockdown of PEX26, a protein involved in peroxisome synthesis, decreased peroxisome content and lipid accumulation during the differentiation of preadipocytes. It has been reported that the abundance of ether lipids in peroxisomes is markedly reduced in the lipid droplets of peroxisome-deficient fibroblasts [55] and intracellular lipids are directly transported between lipid droplets and peroxisomes [51,56]. These findings suggest that peroxisomes are required for the accumulation and maintenance of intracellular lipids.
This study also demonstrated that the inhibition of catalase activity triggered autophagy and a decrease in peroxisome content during the differentiation of preadipocytes. Moreover, an inhibitor of autophagy prevented a decrease in lipid accumulation in adipocytes treated with a catalase inhibitor. While excessive H2O2 levels damage intracellular components and promote cell death, mild levels should play important roles in cell signaling and communication networks that regulate cell functions [49]. H2O2 induces autophagy by activating autophagy-related 4b cysteine peptidase, an autophagy-related enzyme [58]. Autophagy, which is induced by nutritional or energy starvation and activation of various signal transduction pathways and various stressors, is involved in the removal of many cellular components, including protein aggregates, pathogens, and organelles. It has been reported that an increase in ROS in peroxisomes induces autophagy by suppression of mammalian target of rapamycin complex 1 via activation of ataxia telangiectasia mutated [59]. These results indicate that autophagy triggered by increasing H2O2 degradation in peroxisomes participates in lipid synthesis. Furthermore, it has been reported that inhibition of catalase by 3-AT induced a decrease in peroxisome number via pexophagy, a form of selective autophagy, in human liver cancer HepG2 cells during serum starvation [60]. Based on these findings, we inferred that the excess of peroxisomal H2O2 generated by the inhibition of catalase activity caused a decrease in peroxisome content in adipocytes through the occurrence of autophagy.
Obesity is characterized by an increase in adipocyte size and number, which results from an imbalance between energy intake and expenditure. The suppression of adipocyte hypertrophy can prevent and improve obesity-related hypertension, atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease, and diabetes. The results of the present study showed that catalase activity may be necessary for the maintenance of lipid droplets by suppressing the occurrence of autophagy. Lipid droplets are organelles that store excessive lipids and the peroxisomes of most eukaryotes also have multifunctional organelles. Despite the widespread perception that H2O2 can act as a signaling molecule in cellular metabolism, there is much evidence that ROS, such as HO and H2O2, are essentially toxic compounds. Kozdag et al. concluded that a decrease in serum triglyceride levels participated in cardiovascular death in patients with heart failure, but the reasons for the low triglyceride levels are unknown [61]. Since it is an important biological molecule, lower triglyceride levels would impact physiological reactions. The balance of catalase activity and H2O2 concentrations in cells maintain lipid levels. Peroxisomes help maintain cellular homeostasis by recycling lipids and helping to protect cells from oxidative stress and damage. Excessive production of H2O2 induced the lowering of lipid levels and an imbalance in lipid metabolism. Taken together, these findings indicate that peroxisomal catalase regulates peroxisomal contents to maintain an appropriate lipid levels in adipocytes.

5. Conclusion

Here we showed that catalase protects against the degradation of peroxisomes via the occurrence of autophagy triggered by the generation of H2O2 in peroxisomes during the differentiation 3T3-L1 preadipocytes to adipocytes. This work guides new properties in multiple mechanisms underlying lipid accumulation. Consequently, the importance of catalase activity in the lipid accumulation suggests that oxidative stress may be a fundamental mechanism of disorders of lipid metabolism. Further in vivo studies will be necessary to clarify the mechanism underling the obesity development.
